    <body>
        <p>You can natively read your application secrets in <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /> with the <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><a href="https://www.hashicorp.com/products/vault">Hashicorp Vault</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><a href="https://www.cyberark.com/products/privileged-access-manager/">CyberArk PAM Vault</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/secrets-manager/">AWS Secrets Manager</a></MadCap:conditionalText> extension. If you connect to your vault using the <code><MadCap:variable name="General.liquiPropFile" /></code> file, you can store sensitive <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /> authentication details such as database <code>url</code>, <code>username</code>, and <code>password</code>&#160;<MadCap:variable name="General.Param/Attribute" />s and your <MadCap:variable name="General.LBPro" /> license key in your vault.</p>
        <p>For more information, see <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><a href="https://developer.hashicorp.com/vault">HashiCorp Vault documentation</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><a href="https://docs.cyberark.com/Product-Doc/OnlineHelp/PAS/Latest/en/Content/Resources/_TopNav/cc_Home.htm">CyberArk PAM documentation</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/intro.html">AWS Secrets Manager documentation</a></MadCap:conditionalText>.</p>
        <h2 id="requirements">Requirements</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" />&#160;4.1<MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws,secrets.hashicorp">8</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">0</MadCap:conditionalText>.0+</li>
            <li><MadCap:variable name="General.LBPro" /> license. See <MadCap:xref href="../../../workflows/liquibase-pro/how-to-apply-your-liquibase-pro-license-key.htm">How to Apply Your [%=General.LBPro%] License Key</MadCap:xref></li>
            <li MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><a href="https://www.hashicorp.com/products/vault">HashiCorp Vault</a> with V1 API enabled</li>
            <li MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><a href="https://www.cyberark.com/products/privileged-access-manager/">CyberArk PAM Vault</a> with API enabled</li>
            <li MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Root_certificate">RootCA certificate</a> in your Java security keystore (typically <a href="https://www.ibm.com/docs/en/sdk-java-technology/8?topic=certificate-cacerts-certificates-file"><code>cacerts</code></a>)</li>
            <li MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://aws.amazon.com/secrets-manager/">AWS Secrets Manager</a> credentials</li>
        </ul>
        <h2 id="installation">Installation</h2>
        <h3>CLI</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>Navigate to the <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><a href="https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.liquibase.ext.vaults/liquibase-hashicorp-vault">liquibase-hashicorp-vault</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><a href="https://github.com/liquibase/cyberark-pam-plugin/releases/latest">liquibase-cyberark-pam</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.liquibase.ext.vaults/liquibase-aws-secrets-manager">liquibase-aws-secrets-manager</a></MadCap:conditionalText> extension on Maven Central</li>
            <li>Download <code>liquibase-</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">hashicorp-vault</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">cyberarkpam-vault</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">aws-secrets-manager</code><code>-&lt;version&gt;.jar</code> and move it to the <code>liquibase/lib</code> directory</li>
        </ol>
        <h3 MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp,secrets.aws">Maven</h3>
        <p MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp,secrets.aws">If you use Maven, add the <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><a href="https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.liquibase.ext.vaults/liquibase-hashicorp-vault">HashiCorp Vault extension dependency</a></MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://mvnrepository.com/artifact/org.liquibase.ext.vaults/liquibase-aws-secrets-manager">AWS&#160;Secrets Manager extension dependency</a></MadCap:conditionalText> in your <code>pom.xml</code> file to download the JAR:</p><pre xml:space="preserve" MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><code class="language-text">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.liquibase.ext.vaults&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;liquibase-hashicorp-vault&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;1.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre><pre xml:space="preserve" MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><code class="language-text">&lt;dependency&gt;
    &lt;groupId&gt;org.liquibase.ext.vaults&lt;/groupId&gt;
    &lt;artifactId&gt;liquibase-aws-secrets-manager&lt;/artifactId&gt;
    &lt;version&gt;1.0.0&lt;/version&gt;
&lt;/dependency&gt;</code></pre>
        <h3><MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase"></MadCap:variable> Package Manager</h3>
        <p>Alternatively, you can install the <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">HashiCorp Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">CyberArk PAM Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">AWS Secrets Manager</MadCap:conditionalText> extension with <code>lpm</code> (<a href="https://github.com/liquibase/liquibase-package-manager">Liquibase Package Manager</a>).</p><pre xml:space="preserve" MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp"><code class="language-shell">lpm update
lpm add liquibase-hashicorp-vault</code></pre><pre xml:space="preserve" MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><code class="language-shell">lpm update
lpm add cyberarkpam-vault</code></pre><pre xml:space="preserve" MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><code class="language-shell">lpm update
lpm add liquibase-aws-secrets-manager</code></pre>
        <h2 id="setup" MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws,secrets.cyberark">Setup</h2>
        <p MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">You must add a RootCA certificate in your Java security keystore. For example:</p><pre MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark"><code class="language-shell">sudo keytool -importcert -alias CyberArkRoot -keystore /Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/adoptopenjdk-11.jdk/Contents/Home/lib/security/cacerts -storepass changeit -file RootCA.crt</code></pre>
        <p MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">If there is an error message showing PKIX exception, you could have imported into the wrong <code>cacerts</code> file. Run <code>liquibase -version</code> to see which JVM <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase" /> is using</p>
        <p MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">To debug the SSL connection, you can add this Java environment variable to your command line:
<code>-Djavax.net.debug=ssl:handshake</code></p>
        <p MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws"><a href="https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cli/latest/userguide/cli-configure-files.html">Configure your AWS credentials</a> in any standard method. <code>aws_access_key_id</code>, <code>aws_secret_access_key</code> and <code>aws_region</code> are required.</p>
        <h2 id="usage">Usage</h2>
        <p>You can store any <MadCap:variable name="General.Liquibase"></MadCap:variable> property in <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">HashiCorp Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">CyberArk PAM Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">AWS Secrets Manager</MadCap:conditionalText>.</p>
        <ol>
            <li MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark,secrets.hashicorp">Set the <code>VAULT_ADDR</code> and <code MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">VAULT_CERTFILE</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">VAULT_TOKEN</code>&#160;<MadCap:variable name="General.Param/Attribute" />s as <a href="../../../concepts/connections/liquibase-environment-variables.htm">environment variables</a>, as <a href="../../../concepts/connections/java-opts-environment-variable.htm"><code>-D</code> Java system properties</a>, or in your <a href="../../../concepts/connections/creating-config-properties.html"><code><MadCap:variable name="General.liquiPropFile" /></code> file</a>.</li>
            <li>In <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">HashiCorp Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">CyberArk PAM Vault</MadCap:conditionalText><MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">AWS Secrets Manager</MadCap:conditionalText>, configure sensitive properties like your database username, password, URL, and <MadCap:variable name="General.LBPro" /> license key as secrets.</li>
            <li>In your <code><MadCap:variable name="General.liquiPropFile"></MadCap:variable></code> file or other valid configuration location, specify the path to each secret in your vault. Use the syntax <code MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp">VAULT,PATH,FIELD</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.cyberark">VAULT_TYPE,PATH_TO_NAME_IN_PAM,FIELD_TO_MAP</code><code MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">VAULT,SECRET,KEY</code>. <MadCap:conditionalText MadCap:conditions="secrets.aws">You can also enable support for AWS Systems Manager with <code>VAULT,PARAMETER</code>.</MadCap:conditionalText></li>
            <p class="note" MadCap:conditions="secrets.hashicorp" MadCap:autonum="&lt;b&gt;Note: &lt;/b&gt;">If your <code>PATH</code> includes whitespace, you must surround it with quotes. For example: <code>"secret/my path/"</code>.</p>
        </ol>
